f a rape survivor as well as a reflective critique of a society in which women routinely fear and suffer sexual violence.As Brison observes, trauma disrupts memory, severs past from present, and incapacitates the ability to envision a future. Yet the act of bearing witness, she argues, facilitates recovery by integrating the experience into the survivor's life's story. She also argues for the importance, as well as the hazards, of using first-person narratives in understanding not only trauma, but also larger philosophical questions about what we can know and how we should live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aRape victimsxPsychology. 0aRecovered memory. 0aTraumatic shock. 0aVictims of violent crimesxPsychology. 0aVictims of violent crimesxRehabilitation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  aAcademic writing.  aActivism.  aAdult.  aAll things.  aAllergy.  aAnger.  aAnthropologist.  aAnxiety.  aAphasia.  aAssault.  aAttempt.  aAunt.  aAuthor.  aBertrand Russell.  aBlame.  aChildbirth.  aChildhood memory.  aCognition.  aConcept.  aConsciousness.  aCrime.  aCultural heritage.  aDichotomy.  aDirect experience.  aEmotion.  aEncoding (memory).  aFeeling.  aFemininity.  aFirst-person narrative.  aFriendship.  aGenre.  aGrief.  aHate crime.  aHospital bed.  aHumiliation.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIdentity politics.  aIllustration.  aInterdependence.  aInvisibility.  aIrony.  aIrrational number.  aJ. L. Austin.  aJurisprudence.  aMarianne Hirsch.  aMary Joe Frug.  aMedical diagnosis.  aMetaphysics.  aMorphine.  aMother.  aNarrative therapy.  aNarrative.  aNausea.  aNeurochemistry.  aNon-human.  aObstacle.  aPaul Celan.  aPaul Fussell.  aPerformative utterance.  aPersonal identity.  aPersonal